CHAPTER 3: GEOMETRIC FRAMEWORK FOR HAND MODELING

3.1 Mathematical Preliminaries

3.1.1 Lie Groups and the Special Euclidean Group SE(3)

The set of all rigid body motions in three‑dimensional space forms the special Euclidean group SE(3). An element of SE(3) can be represented as a pair $(R, p)$ where $R \in SO(3)$ is a rotation matrix and $p \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is a translation vector. Group multiplication is:

(R_1, p_1) \cdot (R_2, p_2) = (R_1R_2, R_1p_2 + p_1).

SE(3) is a six‑dimensional Lie group. Its Lie algebra $\mathfrak{se}(3)$ consists of twists $\xi = (v, \omega)$ where $v \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is linear velocity and $\omega \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is angular velocity. The exponential map $\exp: \mathfrak{se}(3) \to SE(3)$ converts twists to rigid motions:

\exp(\hat{\xi}) = \begin{bmatrix} e^{\hat{\omega}} & (I - e^{\hat{\omega}})(\omega \times v) + \omega\omega^T v \theta \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix},

where $\hat{\omega}$ is the skew‑symmetric matrix of $\omega$, and $\theta = \|\omega\|$ for nonzero $\omega$.

3.1.2 Screw Theory and the Product of Exponentials

A screw is a geometric entity comprising a line in space (the screw axis) and a pitch. The instantaneous motion of a rigid body can be represented as a twist—the velocity analogue of a screw. For a revolute joint with axis $\omega$ (unit vector) and point $q$ on the axis, the screw axis is:

\mathcal{S} = \begin{bmatrix} -\omega \times q \\ \omega \end{bmatrix}.

For a prismatic joint with direction $v$, the screw axis is:

\mathcal{S} = \begin{bmatrix} v \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}.

The product of exponentials formula expresses the forward kinematics of an n‑joint manipulator as:

T(\theta) = e^{[\mathcal{S}_1]\theta_1}e^{[\mathcal{S}_2]\theta_2}\cdots e^{[\mathcal{S}_n]\theta_n}M,

where $[\mathcal{S}_i]$ is the matrix representation of the screw axis, and $M$ is the home configuration.

3.1.3 Port‑Hamiltonian Systems on Manifolds

A port‑Hamiltonian system is defined on a manifold $\mathcal{X}$ with Hamiltonian $H: \mathcal{X} \to \mathbb{R}$. The dynamics are:

\dot{x} = [J(x) - R(x)]\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x) + g(x)u,


y = g^T(x)\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x),

with $J(x)$ skew‑symmetric, $R(x) \geq 0$, and $(u, y)$ power‑conjugate ports. This formulation preserves the geometric structure and energy properties of the system.

3.2 Kinematic Modeling via Product of Exponentials

3.2.1 Finger as an Open Kinematic Chain

Consider a finger with $n$ joints. Let the base frame be attached to the palm, and let $M \in SE(3)$ be the fingertip pose when all joint angles are zero. For each joint $i$, define a screw axis $\mathcal{S}_i$ expressed in the base frame. The forward kinematics are:

T(\theta) = e^{[\mathcal{S}_1]\theta_1}e^{[\mathcal{S}_2]\theta_2}\cdots e^{[\mathcal{S}_n]\theta_n}M.

For a typical finger, joints alternate between flexion/extension axes (perpendicular to finger plane) and abduction/adduction axes (orthogonal to flexion axes). The screw axes reflect this geometry.

3.2.2 Incorporating Multiple Fingers and the Thumb

A full hand model consists of five fingers, each described by its own product of exponentials. The thumb requires special attention due to its opposable saddle joint, which can be modeled as two intersecting revolute axes.

Let $T_f(\theta_f)$ denote the fingertip pose of finger $f$ as a function of its joint angles $\theta_f$. The overall hand configuration is the tuple $(\theta_1, \ldots, \theta_5)$.

3.2.3 Configuration Space and Its Topology

The configuration space of a single finger is a product of circles (for revolute joints) and lines (for prismatic joints), i.e., an $n$-dimensional torus $\mathbb{T}^n$ if all joints are revolute. For the whole hand, the configuration space is the product of the individual finger spaces:

\mathcal{C} = \mathbb{T}^{n_1} \times \mathbb{T}^{n_2} \times \cdots \times \mathbb{T}^{n_5}.

This space has the topology of a high‑dimensional torus. Understanding its geometry is essential for analyzing hand movements and planning motions.

3.3 Dynamic Modeling with Port‑Hamiltonian Systems

3.3.1 Hamiltonian Formulation for Multi‑Segment Fingers

For a finger with $n$ segments, choose generalized coordinates $q \in \mathbb{R}^n$ (joint angles) and generalized momenta $p = M(q)\dot{q}$, where $M(q)$ is the inertia matrix. The Hamiltonian is:

H(q, p) = \frac{1}{2}p^T M^{-1}(q)p + V(q),

where $V(q)$ includes gravitational and elastic potential energy.

The port‑Hamiltonian dynamics are:

\begin{bmatrix} \dot{q} \\ \dot{p} \end{bmatrix} = \left( \begin{bmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & R(q, p) \end{bmatrix} \right) \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} \\ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ B(q) \end{bmatrix} u,


y = B^T(q) \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = B^T(q) M^{-1}(q)p.

3.3.2 Tendon Transmission and the Coupling Matrix

The input matrix $B(q)$ maps tendon forces $u$ to joint torques. For a tendon‑driven finger with $m$ tendons, the relationship is:

\tau = P^T(q) f,

where $P(q)$ is the coupling matrix (dependent on tendon routing and joint angles). Thus $B(q) = P^T(q)$.

3.3.3 Dissipation and Friction Modeling

Dissipation $R(q, p)$ captures friction at joints and along tendons. A common model is Rayleigh dissipation:

R(q, p) = \text{diag}(0, D(q, \dot{q})),

where $D(q, \dot{q})$ is a positive definite matrix representing joint damping and tendon friction. More sophisticated models (e.g., LuGre) can be incorporated by augmenting the state with internal friction states.

3.4 Underactuation and the Coupling–Adaptation Paradox

3.4.1 Mathematical Characterization of Underactuated Fingers

An underactuated finger has fewer actuators than degrees of freedom: $m < n$. The dynamics become:

\tau = P^T f, \quad \text{rank}(P) = m.

The nullspace of $P^T$ represents directions in torque space that cannot be directly actuated. These directions are governed by passive elements (springs, mechanical limits) and contact forces.

3.4.2 Motion Modes: Coupling vs. Adaptation

During free motion (no contact), the finger follows a trajectory determined by the actuator input and the coupling matrix. The velocity relationship is:

\dot{q} = P^\# \dot{l} + (I - P^\#P)\eta,

where $P^\#$ is a generalized inverse of $P$, and $\eta$ represents nullspace motions. For a well‑designed underactuated finger, the nullspace is constrained by passive elements, leading to a unique motion for each actuator input.

When a phalanx contacts an object, external forces modify the dynamics. The joint stops moving when the contact torque balances the actuation torque. This creates sequential motion: proximal joints move first, then distal joints.

Coupling corresponds to a motion where all joints move simultaneously, i.e., $\dot{q}$ is proportional to a fixed vector $c$ (the coupling pattern). Adaptation corresponds to the ability to stop joints independently upon contact, which requires that the nullspace be sufficiently rich to allow different joint stopping orders.

3.4.3 Toward a Geometric Understanding of the Paradox

The coupling–adaptation paradox can be understood geometrically as a conflict between two desirable properties of the coupling matrix $P$:

· For coupling, we want $P$ to have a one‑dimensional column space aligned with the desired joint motion pattern.
· For adaptation, we want $P$ to have a high‑dimensional nullspace that allows joints to stop independently.

These are opposing requirements: a low‑rank $P$ (strong coupling) gives a small nullspace, limiting adaptation; a high‑rank $P$ (weak coupling) gives a larger nullspace but reduces coordinated motion.

A complete resolution of the paradox requires mechanisms that can change $P$ or introduce additional constraints (e.g., variable stiffness) during the grasp. This dissertation provides the mathematical language to formulate such solutions, even if the detailed mechanism design is left for future work.

